# OrcheStack — Environment variables.
#
# To use:
#   1. Copy this file to `.env` in the same directory.
#   2. Set ORCHESTACK_DB_PASSWORD to a strong value (do NOT use the placeholder).
#   3. Run `docker compose up -d`.
#
# The .env file is gitignored — never commit real secrets.
#
# ============================================================================
# Two-database model — important context
# ============================================================================
# OrcheStack runs TWO logical PostgreSQL databases inside one Postgres container:
#
#   1. The OrcheStack internal database (ORCHESTACK_DB_* below)
#      ─ Holds OrcheStack's own state: users, roles, sessions, audit log,
#        service-pinning, installed-service registry. Schema: `platform`.
#      ─ Small and bounded — does not grow with the volume of your data.
#      ─ Bootstrap credentials. Set ONCE here in .env, before first boot.
#        Cannot be changed from inside the running system because Postgres
#        initialises the superuser on first volume creation only.
#
#   2. The customer pipeline database (collected via the setup wizard)
#      ─ Holds YOUR data: raw landing tables, dbt marts, Airflow metadata.
#      ─ Grows with your business. Different user, different DB name.
#      ─ Created and configured during the in-browser setup wizard
#        (http://localhost/setup/configure → PostgreSQL section). NOT in
#        this file.
#
# Keeping them separate means a backup of OrcheStack's metadata is cheap and
# fast, while pipeline backups can follow your own data-retention policy.
# ============================================================================
ORCHESTACK_DB_USER=orchestack
ORCHESTACK_DB_PASSWORD=changeme-set-a-strong-password-before-running
ORCHESTACK_DB_NAME=orchestack_db

# ============================================================================
# Image tags.
# Pin to a specific immutable version (e.g. 0.1.0) in production deployments
# so an upstream rebuild doesn't silently change behaviour. `latest` is fine
# for development and CI smoke tests.
# ============================================================================
AUTH_TAG=latest
ORCHESTRATOR_TAG=latest
DASHBOARD_TAG=latest
# AIRFLOW_TAG=latest        # uncomment at M4

# ============================================================================
# Host port mappings.
# Override these if port 80/443 are already in use on the host, or if you
# want to expose OrcheStack on a non-standard port for development.
# Examples:
#   PROXY_HTTP_PORT=1993        → http://localhost:1993
#   PROXY_HTTPS_PORT=1994       → https://localhost:1994
#   PROXY_DASHBOARD_PORT=18080  → http://localhost:18080/dashboard/
# Leave commented to use the defaults (80, 443, 8080).
# ============================================================================
# PROXY_HTTP_PORT=80
# PROXY_HTTPS_PORT=443
# PROXY_DASHBOARD_PORT=8080
